<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="homework" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Homework assignments</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-hw-01">
    <title>HW 01</title>
    <p>
      Note: These statements should be proved using only the definitions and
      properties presented in the lecture notes.
      <ol marker="1.">
        <li>
          <p>
            Show that, for all <m>a, b, c \in \N</m>, the following are true.
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li xml:id="hw-01-cancel-addition">
                <p>
                  If <m>a + c = b + c</m>, then <m>a = b</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="hw-01-cancel-multiplication">
                <p>
                  If <m>ac = bc</m>, then <m>a = b</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="hw-01-addition-preserves-order">
                <p>
                  We have <m>a \lt b</m> if and only if <m>a + c \lt b + c</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li xml:id="hw-01-successor-fixpoint-free">
                <p>
                  Prove that <m>n \ne n + 1</m> for all <m>n \in \N</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="hw-01-addition-not-nilpotent">
                <p>
                  Use <xref text="local" ref="hw-01-successor-fixpoint-free"/> to
                  prove that <m>n \ne n + k</m> for all <m>n, k \in \N</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Prove the following identities hold for all <m>x, y \in \Z</m>. You
            may freely use any corresponding properties of <m>\N</m>.
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li xml:id="hw-01-integer-addition-commutative">
                <p>
                  <m>x + y = y + x</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="hw-01-zero-additive-identity">
                <p>
                  <m>x + \overline{0} = x</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="hw-01-x-minus-x-is-0">
                <p>
                  <m>x - x = \overline{0}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="hw-01-multiplication-well-defined">
          <p>
            Show that multiplication in <m>\Z</m>, defined by
            <me>
              [(a,b)] \cdot [(c, d)] = [(ac + bd, ad + bc)]
            </me>
            is well-defined.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For <m>[(a, b)] \in \Z</m>, show that <m>[(a, b)] = \overline{0}</m>
            if and only if <m>a = b</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For <m>[(a, b)] \in \Z</m>, show that <m>\overline{0} \lt [(a,b)]</m>
            if and only if <m>b \lt a</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For <m>x, y, z \in \Z</m>, prove the following.
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>xy = \overline{0}</m> then <m>x = \overline{0}</m>
                  or <m>y = \overline{0}</m>. Hint: Suppose <m>x \ne \overline{0}</m>
                  and split into cases <m>x \lt \overline{0}</m>
                  and <m>\overline{0} \lt x</m>. Use the results of previous
                  problems.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>x \lt y</m> and <m>\overline{0} \lt z</m>, then
                  <m>xz \lt yz</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For <m>x, y \in \Z</m>, we write <m>x \leq y</m> if
            either <m>x \lt y</m> or <m>x = y</m>. Prove that <m>\leq</m>
            is a <em>partial order</em>. That is, prove the following
            are true for all <m>x, y, z \in \Z</m>.
            <ol marker="i.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>x \leq x</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>x \leq y</m> and <m>y \leq x</m>, then <m>x = y</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>x \leq y</m> and <m>y \leq z</m>, then <m>x \leq z</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
            (For the last two parts you will probably want to divide into cases.)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-hw-02">
    <title>HW 02</title>
    <p>
      Note: These statements should be proved using only the definitions and
      properties presented in the lecture notes.
    </p>
    <exercises>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show that the equivalence relation of
            <xref ref="def-rational-equiv-classes"/> is an equivalence
            relation.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove <xref ref="prop-archimedean-property"/>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            A rational
            number <m>x</m> satisfies exactly one of <m>x \lt 0</m>, 
            <m>x = 0</m>, or <m>x \gt 0</m>, so divide into cases based 
            on these.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that if <m>x, y \in \Q</m>, then there exists <m>z \in \Q</m>
            with <m>x \lt z \lt y</m>. You may use any of the standard
            properties of the relation <m>\lt</m> on <m>\Q</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>\abs{xy} = \abs{x}\abs{y}</m> for all <m>x, y \in \Q</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove the result of <xref ref="li-intervals-absolute-value"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use <xref ref="li-triangle-ineq">the Triangle Inequality</xref> 
            to prove 
            <xref ref="li-reverse-triangle-ineq">the Reverse Triangle Inequality</xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>a_n</m> and <m>b_n</m> are Cauchy sequences of rational
            numbers, prove that the sequence <m>c_n = a_n + b_n</m> is 
            also Cauchy.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercises>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-hw-03">
    <title>HW 03</title>
    <p>
      Note: These statements should be proved using only the definitions and
      properties presented in the lecture notes, as well as the additional
      definitions below.
    </p>
    <p>
      Consider a subset <m>A</m> of <m>\R</m>. We say that <m>M \in \R</m>
      is a lower bound for <m>A</m> if <m>x \geq M</m> for all 
      <m>x \in A</m>. We say that <m>M</m> is a greatest lower bound
      for <m>A</m> if, for all lower bounds <m>M'</m> of <m>A</m>, we 
      have <m>M \geq M'</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Greatest lower bounds are unique when they exist, and every nonempty
      subset of <m>\R</m> that has a lower bound has a greatest lower bound.
      You can assume all this without proof for the rest of the HW 03.
    </p>
    <p>
      The greatest lower bound of a set <m>A</m> (provided it exists) 
      is also called the infimum of <m>A</m> and written <m>\inf{(A)}</m>.
    </p>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-hw-03">
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>x, y \in \R</m>. Prove that if <m>x, y \gt 0</m>, then
            <m>x + y \gt 0</m> and <m>xy \gt 0</m>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Use the definition of a real number as an equivalence class of
            Cauchy sequences of rational numbers.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>a_n</m> be a Cauchy sequence of rational numbers and let
            <m>x \in \R</m>. Show that if <m>a_n \leq x</m> for all <m>n \in \N</m>, 
            then <m>[a_n] \leq x</m>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Use a proof by contradiction. If <m>[a_n] \gt x</m>, then there
            exists <m>r \in \Q</m> such that <m>[a_n] \gt r \gt x</m> (why?).
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>B \subseteq A \subseteq \R</m> are nonempty and that
            <m>A</m> has an upper bound. 
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Show that <m>B</m> has an upper bound.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Show that <m>\sup{(B)} \leq \sup{(A)}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>A, B \subseteq \R</m> each have an upper bound.
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Show <m>A \cup B</m> has an upper bound.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find a formula for <m>\sup{(A \cup B)}</m>. Prove your result.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A \subseteq \R</m> be nonempty and suppose <m>A</m> has an
            upper bound. Let <m>M = \sup{(A)}</m> and define the set <m>-A</m>
            by <me>
              -A = \{ -x : x \in A \}
            </me>.
            Prove that <m>-M = \inf{(-A)}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose that <m>A \subseteq \R</m> is nonempty. 
            Show that if <m>M</m> is a lower bound for <m>A</m>, then
            <m>M = \inf{(A)}</m> if and only if for every real number
            <m>\eps \gt 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> such that 
            <m>a \lt M + \eps</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the supremum and infimum of the set <me>
              \left\{ \frac{m}{m+n} : m, n \in \N \right\}
            </me>. Prove your results.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>\mathbf{I} = \{ x \in \R : x \not\in \Q \}</m> be the
                  set of <em>irrational</em> numbers. Show that if <m>x \in \Q</m>
                  and <m>y \in \mathbf{I}</m>, then <m>x + y \in \mathbf{I}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the previous part and the density of <m>\Q</m> in <m>\R</m>
                  to prove that <m>I</m> is also dense in <m>\R</m>. That is, if
                  <m>x \lt y</m> for <m>x, y \in \R</m>, prove that there exists
                  <m>t \in \mathbf{I}</m> such that <m>x \lt t \lt y</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Apply the density result to <m>x - \sqrt{2} \lt y - \sqrt{2}</m>.
            You may assume <m>\sqrt{2} \in \mathbf{I}</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>
    </exercises>
  </subsection>
</section>
